Elemental analysis of the CQD was conducted by XPS analysis. Three distinct XPS peaks at 283.46, 405, and 534.16 eV in the XPS scan account for the C 1 s peak of carbon, N 1 s peak of nitrogen, and O 1 s peak of oxygen (Fig. 3
                        a). Characteristic peaks at 284.62, 286.72, and 288.6 eV exhibited in the high-resolution spectra of C 1 s, may correspond to CC, CO, and CO, respectively (Fig. 3b) and the high-resolution spectra of N 1 s exhibited two peaks at 399.59, and 401.38 eV (Fig. 3c). The high-resolution spectra of O 1 s showed peaks at 531.52, 532.41, and 533.17 eV, corresponding to CO, CO, and C-OH/COC, respectively (Fig. 3d). The FTIR spectrum shows an absorption peak around 3335 cm−1, which belongs to the stretching vibration of the hydroxyl (–OH) group. The absorption peak observed at 1633, 1390, and 1038 cm−1 correspond to CC stretching, NH, and CO stretching (Fig. 4
                        ) [11].

Reaction conditions were optimized to obtain the most exemplary performance of the sensor. Maximum intensity was obtained at pH 6 (
                           Fig. S2
                        ) and is the optimized pH for further experiments. The selectivity of CQD towards Fe(II) was tested with different metal ions (Zn(II), Ag(II), Fe(II), Cd(II), Ni(II), Cu(II), Mn(II), Hg(II), Cr(III), and Co(II)) (Fig. 7
                        a). The zeta potential value measured was −9.8 mV, indicating a negative charge on CQD (
                           Fig. S3
                        ). A negative zeta potential value suggests that the electrostatic forces between the molecules are repulsive [37,38]. Thus sensing arises by the interaction of positively charged metal ions and negatively charged surface of CQDs. The effect of the concentration of Fe(II) on PL intensity was analyzed in the concentration range 0–50 μM (Fig. 7b), PL intensity decreases linearly with concentration. The interaction of hydroxyl and amino groups on the CQD surface with Fe(II) ions reduced fluorescence intensity. As a result, the energy was released through non-radiative recombination [38]. A linear relationship between quenching intensity and Fe(II) was observed with a lower detection limit(LOD) of 0.517 µM (Fig. 7c). The performance of the sensor was further evaluated by conducting an interference study by adding different metal ion solutions to CQD solution containing Fe(II) ions (Fig. 7d). Even in the presence of interfering ions, Fe(II) quenches the florescent intensity of CQDs. These results showed that the suggested device could be used as a fluorescence probe to detect Fe(II) ions.
